    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Attacks in the Park</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Yale H Gellman letter on attacks on women in Central Park on Puerto Rican Day; notes that police officers on horseback, with radios, can be very effective in controlling such mobs (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has said that one of the reasons for the slow response to the attacks in Central Park is that ''it is unrealistic to assume that police officers can be everywhere at all times, particularly when they are dealing with a parade'' (front page, June 13).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has said that one of the reasons for the slow response to the attacks in Central Park is that ''it is unrealistic to assume that police officers can be everywhere at all times, particularly when they are dealing with a parade'' (front page, June 13).</p>
        <p>But there is a remedy that has worked before. Twenty or 30 police officers on horseback in the park, with radios and backed up by a mobile unit, could be very effective both as a deterrent and as a means of summoning aid.</p>
        <p>YALE H. GELLMAN  Great Neck, N.Y., June 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
